  "text": "When females of the lake ecotype were confronted with a choice of four (the 'lake mimic') or two (the 'river mimic') peptide cocktails in the flow chamber experiment, lake females spent significantly more time in front of the four-peptide inlet compared to the one with two peptides (figure 2b; n ¼ 12, t 18 ¼ 23.9659, p ¼ 0.00091, two-tailed paired t-test). The river females, by contrast, significantly preferred the two-peptide signal (figure 2b; n ¼ 14, t 25 ¼ 2.4822, p ¼ 0.021). Females thus showed a significant preference for their habitat-specific synthetic MHC allele number. Control experiments corroborated that the male validation factor, which is required for accurate interpretation of the MHC-based signal by female sticklebacks [CITATION_1] , is invariant between lake and river males [CITATION_2] . Indeed, the preference for either two-peptide or four-peptide mimics was independent of the male's population of origin, both for the river (n ¼ 12, t 22 ¼ 21.0063, p ¼ 0.33) or the lake (n ¼ 12, t 21 ¼ 20.16543, p ¼ 0.87), i.e. when the male providing the validation factor was either a river or a lake male for both the two-and the four-peptide inlet.",
